# TypeScript Style & Typing Rules

- Prefer `unknown` over `any`. Never cast to `any`. Narrow with type guards.
- Use `import type { ... }` for types. Keep value/type imports separate.
- Exported APIs and public functions should have explicit parameter and return types.
- Prefer early returns and guard clauses; avoid deep nesting.
- Name functions as verbs; variables and constants as nouns. Avoid abbreviations.
- Use generics for reusable logic. Avoid over-broad types.
- Never swallow errors. Convert unknown errors to strings via a helper (see `errorToString` in [`src/index.ts`](mdc:src/index.ts)).
- Keep modules small and single-responsibility. Cross-module imports should respect boundaries documented in the Architecture Guide.
- Avoid side effects in modules except the CLI entrypoint.
- Never log raw secrets; rely on the redacting logger.